These are the defaults, which we do in other inventory items. Ack.
.........  Any more details here?  You implemented two properties, but you don't specify why a user would care, or use these two properties.
Ack

This is a pretty standard State / Health like we do elsewhere..
 
But not sure you have really answered Ed's comment.. Can you add a line like "Like other Redfish resources implement State/Health and map them to Present/Functional respectfully. State / Health of the Port is useful information for inventory on a GUI/Debug/etc."
Done
Done
This property is being set on both lines 102 and here.  As written, these two functions are a race if present == false and functional == false.  it's inconsistent which will be written.

We do this in several other places in the code e.g. 
https://github.com/openbmc/bmcweb/blob/7a696974d7a987e3eb135a6cbad0a4ace8d109d2/redfish-core/lib/fan.hpp#L276
https://github.com/openbmc/bmcweb/blob/7a696974d7a987e3eb135a6cbad0a4ace8d109d2/redfish-core/lib/fan.hpp#L251
Non trivial lambda.  This is a documented anti-pattern.
Refactored.

I am good with this being refactored but at https://github.com/openbmc/bmcweb/blob/7a696974d7a987e3eb135a6cbad0a4ace8d109d2/COMMON_ERRORS.md#14-very-long-lambda-callbacks 
"keep the lambda length less than 10 lines"
These seem right on the edge
Why const bool?

There are several places that use `const bool` for this kind of the functions.
But I agree that `const` is not needed for this basic types.
I changed to `bool`.
Feel free to fix any place that uses const bool for these kinds of the functions

After second thought, I think 'const bool' seems appropriate as the variable from dbus-callback is not supposed to be modifiable inside lambda body?

This way will prevent any mistake that the user changes the variable inside the function.

For example, this mistake will cause the compiler error.

```
        [asyncResp](const boost::system::error_code& ec,
                    const bool functional) {
                    
                    ...
                    functional = true; // <-- compiler will check this error
````

However, if we use 'bool', the variable may be reused inside the body.


```
        [asyncResp](const boost::system::error_code& ec,
                    bool functional) {
                    
                    ...
                    functional = true; // <-- compiler will allow this.
````
Same here.  non trivial lambda
Refactored.
I think afterGetFabricPortState would fit better with the rest of the code but fine as is.
Done
